ionRevisions","id":"64417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64417"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBladder cancer is one of the most common urological malignancies. The three main types are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrothelial carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdenocarcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost of these tumours are urothelial carcinomas and they usually present with painless haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a predisposing factor for bladder cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exposure to aromatic amines","Female gender","High dietary fibre intake","Regular exercise","Young age"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESmoking and exposure to certain chemicals, such as aromatic amines, are important risk factors increase the likelihood of developing bladder cancer in industrialised countries. Smoking accounts for about 50% of cases. With regards to the listed options:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeing female\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - bladder cancer is three times more common in men than women\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExposure to aromatic amines\u003C/strong\u003E is correct - occupational exposure to these chemicals (common in dye, rubber, and leather industries) significantly increases bladder cancer risk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular exercise\u003C/strong\u003E is not a risk factor and may actually be protective\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh dietary fibre intake\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with bladder cancer risk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYoung age\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - bladder cancer risk increases with age, with most cases occurring after age 65\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors include chronic urinary tract infections, and schistosomiasis infection in endemic areas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bladder cancer is more common in men than women with a 3:1 ratio.","Occupational exposure to aromatic amines is a major risk factor for bladder cancer and chronic urinary tract infections and schistosomiasis  also increase bladder cancer risk."],"references":["Comp\u00e9rat E, Amin MB, Cathomas R, Choudhury A, De Santis M, Kamat A, Stenzl A, Thoeny HC, Witjes JA. Current best practice for bladder cancer: a narrative review of diagnostics and treatments. Lancet. 2022 Nov 12;400(10364):1712-1721. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(22)01188-6. Epub 2022 Sep 26. PMID: 36174585.","Lenis AT, Lec PM, Chamie K, Mshs MD. Bladder Cancer: A Review. JAMA. 2020 Nov 17;324(19):1980-1991. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.17598. PMID: 33201207.","Leslie SW, Soon-Sutton TL, Aeddula NR. Bladder Cancer. 2024 Aug 15. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725608.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49849"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15080"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49849"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T16:45:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T16:46:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7768"}},"content"